WEBVTT

00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:07.000
I'm an applied statistician working at a university. My primary goal is helping my collaborators make sense of their data.

00:00:08.500 --> 00:00:15.000
I'm an applied statistician working at a university. My primary goal is helping my collaborators

00:00:16.500 --> 00:00:23.000
make sense of their data. Secondarily is to try to develop new statistical methods to

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:30.000
make sense of their data. Thirdly, to implement those methods in software. For nearly 20 years

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:41.000
I've been working on an R package called RQTL. I want to tell you about that experience.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:01:01.000
The idea for this package came from a friend of mine visited and we were talking about

00:01:02.900 --> 00:01:09.900
the need for specialized software in the applications that we worked in. It was actually the week

00:01:10.540 --> 00:01:17.540
that R version 1 came out in January of 2000. He wanted to write it in MATLAB and I wanted

00:01:18.540 --> 00:01:25.540
to write it as an R package. I was five years younger and devoted more time to it, so it

00:01:26.540 --> 00:01:33.540
became an R package. This figure shows lines of code over time. Each dot is one CRAN release.

00:01:38.339 --> 00:01:45.339
It was first on CRAN at the end of 2001. It's grown to be nearly 40,000 lines of R code

00:01:45.339 --> 00:01:52.339
and 25,000 lines of C code. Over 15,000 lines of the dot RD documentation. Back in the day

00:01:58.620 --> 00:02:05.620
we typed by hand. This didn't actually, for the first seven years it was without version

00:02:06.620 --> 00:02:13.619
control. The way I kept track of versions is by tarring up the file at its current state

00:02:17.740 --> 00:02:24.740
and just saving that tar GZ file. I didn't get into version control until 2008.

00:02:24.740 --> 00:02:31.740
You'll see what my experience has been, I guess. I feel like I should tell you a little

00:02:42.580 --> 00:02:47.220
bit about the package. In doing so, I really need to tell you a little bit about the science.

00:02:47.220 --> 00:02:53.820
I studied genetics of complex traits, mostly in mice. Mice have a big advantage for genetics

00:02:53.860 --> 00:02:59.179
in that you can make inbred lines. You can take a pair of mice and mate them and then

00:02:59.179 --> 00:03:06.179
do repeated mating between siblings for 20 generations or 200 generations. What you get

00:03:06.539 --> 00:03:12.139
at the end is a strain of mice that are all genetically identical. If you can figure out

00:03:12.139 --> 00:03:17.619
which one is a male and which one is a female, cross them, the offspring will all be genetically

00:03:17.619 --> 00:03:24.059
identical again. The advantage for genetics really is simplifying a lot of things and

00:03:24.059 --> 00:03:31.059
being able to make really large crosses. Our interest in the genetics in mice is really

00:03:34.160 --> 00:03:39.380
focused on understanding the genetics of human disease. We're not trying to cure disease

00:03:39.380 --> 00:03:46.380
in mice. We're trying to have a better understanding of the underlying biology of human disease.

00:03:48.139 --> 00:03:54.979
The basic experiment that's done, it would be an intercross where you take two strains

00:03:54.979 --> 00:04:01.100
of mice that differ in some trait. One strain has high blood pressure. The other strain

00:04:01.100 --> 00:04:04.740
has low blood pressure. You're trying to find what genes are contributing to that difference

00:04:04.740 --> 00:04:11.740
in blood pressure. You do a cross that's identical to what Mendel did with his peas to mix up

00:04:12.740 --> 00:04:19.739
the high blood pressure chromosomes and the low blood pressure chromosomes. Then what

00:04:20.420 --> 00:04:27.420
you're going to do is get a bunch of offspring, measure blood pressure in all those mice,

00:04:28.820 --> 00:04:35.140
which really for that phenotype would be the hardest part of this study. Measure the blood

00:04:35.140 --> 00:04:40.579
pressure of all those offspring and measure genotype along each chromosome. Whether a

00:04:40.619 --> 00:04:46.859
mouse is blue-blue, pink-pink, or blue-pink at a given position. Then we're going to scan

00:04:46.859 --> 00:04:52.059
across the genome and look for reasons of the genome where there's an association between

00:04:52.059 --> 00:04:57.459
what genotype you have, whether you were blue-blue, blue-pink, or pink-pink, whether that's associated

00:04:57.459 --> 00:05:04.459
with the outcome blood pressure. The results of this sort of analysis is a plot across

00:05:05.459 --> 00:05:12.459
the mouse genome on each chromosome, the curves for a test statistic that's indicating when

00:05:14.339 --> 00:05:19.940
this thing is high, you are saying there's evidence for an association between genotype

00:05:19.940 --> 00:05:26.940
at that location and blood pressure. Those peaks we call QTL or quantitative trait loci,

00:05:27.859 --> 00:05:34.859
a region of the genome that is affecting a quantitative trait blood pressure. Effectively

00:05:37.579 --> 00:05:42.980
what you do is at every position in the genome you do an analysis of variance to see is there

00:05:42.980 --> 00:05:49.980
a difference in the average trait across the three genotypes. The goal of my package RQTL

00:05:49.980 --> 00:05:56.980
is called QTL because we call these sites we're looking for QTL, the genetic loci that

00:05:59.859 --> 00:06:05.500
affect this quantitative trait. It does a bunch of other things.

00:06:05.500 --> 00:06:12.500
Going back to the package, I just want to talk a little bit about the state of it and

00:06:13.500 --> 00:06:20.500
my experience with it. 20 years into a project, there may be some good things about it, but

00:06:22.500 --> 00:06:29.500
they start to become harder to identify. Some of the code in this package is really good

00:06:33.500 --> 00:06:40.500
and I'm proud of it. Some aspects of the interface, the user interface, what the user interface

00:06:41.500 --> 00:06:47.619
is, the code that the user types to get something to happen, I think was a good idea that I

00:06:47.619 --> 00:06:54.619
had back in 2000, 2001. It includes a lot of data diagnostics features and data visualization

00:07:00.019 --> 00:07:04.420
and it's quite comprehensive. I had this idea that I would implement all methods good and

00:07:04.420 --> 00:07:10.899
bad so that you would have one place that you could try things out and understand them.

00:07:10.899 --> 00:07:17.899
It's quite flexible. I can implement new ideas for analyzing data with this. Other people

00:07:17.940 --> 00:07:24.940
could potentially do so as well. It's easier for me to think about the bad things.

00:07:25.940 --> 00:07:32.940
The first example I want to give is just about getting data into R for this kind of cross.

00:07:37.940 --> 00:07:44.940
For this sort of experiment, I need a set of traits and then genotype data of are you

00:07:46.940 --> 00:07:51.700
blue, blue, blue, pink, pink, pink at sites along the genome. Then I need to know where

00:07:51.700 --> 00:07:57.540
those positions are in the genome. The main input format we use is just a comma delimited

00:07:57.540 --> 00:08:03.859
format where the first few columns are all phenotypes and the traits and then the remaining

00:08:03.859 --> 00:08:10.059
columns are all positions in the genome and their genotypes. The first row has for those

00:08:10.059 --> 00:08:16.940
later columns with the markers, the sites in the genome, it has their chromosome ID.

00:08:16.940 --> 00:08:22.739
The third row has their position. The first thing I do reading this in is I need to split

00:08:22.739 --> 00:08:29.739
the trait data from the genotype data, which I do by looking for where's the first non-blank

00:08:30.019 --> 00:08:37.020
cell in that. As RQTL was used, people started to load in data with lots of traits, like

00:08:38.020 --> 00:08:45.020
say 25,000 traits. They would ask me why is it taking so long to load the data? I would

00:08:49.739 --> 00:08:55.260
say how much data do you have? They'd say 25,000 phenotypes. I'd say it's going to take

00:08:55.260 --> 00:09:02.020
a while. It's a big data set. Then I had a collaboration where I had data that was 20,000

00:09:02.219 --> 00:09:07.940
traits. It was like 20,000 phenotypes and then the usual kind of markers and maybe 300

00:09:07.940 --> 00:09:14.940
mice. It took a minute to load this CSV file into R. I was like something's wrong. It shouldn't

00:09:17.260 --> 00:09:23.260
take a minute to load a file that's really not very big.

00:09:23.260 --> 00:09:30.260
So I looked into the code, which I declare to be the stupidest thing I've ever done.

00:09:32.820 --> 00:09:39.820
It's the stupidest code ever. This code is trying to find the first non-blank cell in

00:09:39.900 --> 00:09:46.900
that sort of second row. It does that by looping from 1 to N, where N is the number of columns.

00:09:50.260 --> 00:09:55.700
It first says is the first cell blank? Is the second cell blank? Are the first two cells

00:09:55.700 --> 00:10:00.619
blank? Are all three of the first cells blank? Are the first four cells blank? Are the first

00:10:00.739 --> 00:10:06.940
five cells all blank? When that fails and it breaks out of that loop, and then it does

00:10:06.940 --> 00:10:13.940
a bit of extra work of trying to find that.

00:10:13.979 --> 00:10:20.979
In loading my data with 25,000 columns of traits, that took about a minute. It was about

00:10:21.099 --> 00:10:28.099
58 seconds was spent on this for loop and two seconds was actually the loading the data

00:10:28.380 --> 00:10:35.380
and everything else.

00:10:39.539 --> 00:10:46.539
I like to say open source means everyone can see my stupid mistakes. And version control

00:10:50.700 --> 00:10:57.700
means everyone can see every stupid mistake I've ever made.

00:10:59.099 --> 00:11:06.099
So, that's not the only bad. That code is no longer in the package. You can find it

00:11:09.539 --> 00:11:16.539
in version control. It's on GitHub. But there is other bad code that's in the package.

00:11:19.299 --> 00:11:24.780
One of the R functions that does sort of a major thing of a two-dimensional scan of the

00:11:24.780 --> 00:11:31.780
genome to try to look for a pair of these QTL is 1,400 lines long, which is not, I mean

00:11:32.859 --> 00:11:39.099
the function is 1,400 lines long. And the C code, I mentioned that this package has

00:11:39.099 --> 00:11:45.419
almost 25,000 lines of C code. Almost 20% of that is related to this one sort of thing

00:11:45.419 --> 00:11:52.419
that I'm trying to do. I mean, it's complicated, but it's also complicated and not really,

00:11:53.419 --> 00:12:00.419
I mean, yeah. It's not what I would do today. The package, I'm really happy with the interface

00:12:08.340 --> 00:12:13.739
for the users. I'm less happy with maybe the data structures that I set up in the year

00:12:13.739 --> 00:12:20.739
2000. There's some really pretty baroque data structures, to put it nicely. This is a bit

00:12:21.619 --> 00:12:28.619
of code that I actually do type because it's something that I want to do. So, there's some

00:12:29.380 --> 00:12:34.299
stuff that you want that's kind of deep inside some really complicated object. There are

00:12:34.299 --> 00:12:38.820
lots of inconsistencies in the code. You have functions that are doing kind of similar things

00:12:38.820 --> 00:12:45.820
that have names that don't, like they're not designed. They're not designed. And they have

00:12:46.700 --> 00:12:51.419
arguments that are really the same argument, but the two different functions have different

00:12:51.419 --> 00:12:56.419
names for that argument. You know, a marker might be marker, or it might be M name one.

00:12:56.419 --> 00:13:01.419
I would say that maybe the biggest mistake I've made has been really useless warning

00:13:06.940 --> 00:13:13.940
messages. A lot of users of RQTL, this is their first experience with R. Their first

00:13:14.500 --> 00:13:21.500
experience with software other than Excel and web browsers, maybe, and Word. So, they

00:13:24.020 --> 00:13:30.099
get a warning message, X prime X is singular. What are they supposed to do with that? What

00:13:30.099 --> 00:13:36.299
does that mean to them? And so, a lot of the questions I get are, I get this warning message,

00:13:36.299 --> 00:13:43.299
X prime X is singular. What should I do? And I think, in looking at this yesterday, I think

00:13:44.140 --> 00:13:49.580
X prime X, you know, I know what that means, but I would, that could be a picture of something,

