did test it. There's not enough planning. I would say, you know, I mean, personal weaknesses.

00:16:09.039 --> 00:16:16.039
There are tradeoffs to make that maybe I made the wrong choices. A couple other quickly

00:16:22.659 --> 00:16:27.700
things that I've learned making RQTL is that, you know, when you're writing documentation

00:16:27.700 --> 00:16:34.700
for a package, what users care about is tailored examples. You know, show me your package in

00:16:34.940 --> 00:16:40.299
action doing exactly what I want to do. So, I could like plug in my data at the top and

00:16:40.299 --> 00:16:44.940
run it, do just what you did. And so, if you're gonna put effort into documentation, it's

00:16:44.940 --> 00:16:49.659
really think about how people are gonna use it and focus on that first. Kind of a general

00:16:49.659 --> 00:16:56.659
user guide sort of second. Examples within the detailed documentation third. Formal documentation,

00:16:57.059 --> 00:17:04.060
it seems like it's important, but no one, I mean, seems to read it.

00:17:04.660 --> 00:17:09.900
User support, I put a lot of effort into answering people's questions. I get emails a couple

00:17:09.900 --> 00:17:16.900
times a week at least still. And I think if you want people to continue to use your software,

00:17:19.660 --> 00:17:26.060
you really need to help them to get started. And so, I mean, and so I'm, I really want

00:17:26.060 --> 00:17:33.060
to make myself useful. If they need help getting their data into RQTL, I'm happy to have them

00:17:33.780 --> 00:17:38.380
send me the data and I'll figure out what's going on and send them code and their data

00:17:38.380 --> 00:17:45.380
back or fixed code. I mean, fixed data that works.

